    <!-- TIPS -->
    <div class="sub-panel active" id="sub-tips">
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-disease">GERD</div>
        <div class="tip-hook">"The fire that goes UP."</div>
        <div class="tip-body">Acid normally stays in the stomach — in GERD it <span>refluxes upward</span> into the esophagus because the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) fails. Think of it as a chimney in reverse. Heartburn after lying down or eating spicy food is the classic story.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-disease">IBS — Irritable Bowel Syndrome</div>
        <div class="tip-hook">"Irritable but intact — no damage, just drama."</div>
        <div class="tip-body">The most important thing to remember: <span>IBS causes zero structural damage.</span> The colon looks completely normal — it just overreacts. Stress is a huge trigger. The alternating constipation and diarrhea is the hallmark. <span>Functional disorder, not inflammatory.</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-disease">Gallstones</div>
        <div class="tip-hook">"Fat triggers the stone."</div>
        <div class="tip-body">Gallstones are usually <span>hardened cholesterol crystals</span> in the gallbladder. When you eat fatty food the gallbladder contracts to push bile out — if a stone blocks the duct, <span>sharp RUQ pain</span> hits. Treatment is just removing the whole gallbladder (cholecystectomy). You don't need it to survive.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-disease">Gastric Ulcers</div>
        <div class="tip-hook">"Empty stomach = burning."</div>
        <div class="tip-body">Ulcers are <span>sores in the stomach lining</span> — caused by H. pylori bacteria eating through the protective mucus layer, or by overusing NSAIDs (ibuprofen, aspirin). Pain is <span>worst when the stomach is empty</span> — no food to buffer the acid. PPIs lower the acid; antibiotics kill H. pylori.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

