    <!-- DNA / PROTEIN SYNTHESIS -->
    <div class="sub-panel2" id="sub2-dna">
      <div class="section-label" style="margin-top:0">DNA &amp; Protein Synthesis — Questions</div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d1">
        <div class="q-num">Question 1</div>
        <div class="q-text">How many ways does <span class="key">RNA differ from DNA</span>? Name them.</div>
        <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="toggleAnswer('d1ans', this)">Show answer</button>
        <div class="answer-box" id="d1ans">
          <strong>3 differences:</strong><br>
          1. RNA is <strong>single-stranded</strong>; DNA is double-stranded.<br>
          2. RNA has <strong>ribose</strong> sugar; DNA has deoxyribose.<br>
          3. RNA uses <strong>uracil (U)</strong> instead of thymine (T).
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d2">
        <div class="q-num">Question 2</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is a <span class="key">codon</span>?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d2',false)">A single base on DNA</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d2',false)">A sequence of 2 bases on tRNA</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d2',true)">Every 3 bases on mRNA that codes for a specific amino acid</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d2',false)">The sugar-phosphate backbone of RNA</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d2-fb">Every 3 bases on mRNA = one codon, which codes for one specific amino acid. The sequence of codons determines the amino acid sequence of the protein.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d3">
        <div class="q-num">Question 3</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is the <span class="key">start codon</span> and what amino acid does it code for?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d3',false)">UAA → Stop</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d3',true)">AUG → Methionine</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d3',false)">UUU → Phenylalanine</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d3',false)">UAG → Stop</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d3-fb">AUG is the universal start codon — it codes for methionine and signals the ribosome to begin translation. Every protein starts with methionine (though it may be removed later).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d4">
        <div class="q-num">Question 4</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is the role of <span class="key">tRNA</span> during translation?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d4',false)">Makes up the ribosome structure</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d4',false)">Carries the genetic code from the nucleus</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d4',true)">Carries amino acids to the ribosome and matches anti-codons to mRNA codons</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d4',false)">Unzips the DNA double helix</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d4-fb">tRNA (transfer RNA) has an amino acid on one end and an anti-codon on the other. It brings the correct amino acid to the ribosome by matching its anti-codon to the mRNA codon.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d5">
        <div class="q-num">Question 5</div>
        <div class="q-text">Where does <span class="key">translation</span> occur?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d5',false)">Nucleus</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d5',false)">Mitochondria</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d5',true)">Ribosome (in the cytoplasm)</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d5',false)">Cell membrane</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d5-fb">Ribosome — mRNA leaves the nucleus, moves into the cytoplasm, and reaches the ribosome where the genetic code is translated into an amino acid sequence (protein).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d6">
        <div class="q-num">Question 6</div>
        <div class="q-text">What type of bond forms between amino acids during translation?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d6',false)">Hydrogen bond</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d6',true)">Peptide bond</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d6',false)">Ionic bond</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d6',false)">Covalent bond</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d6-fb">Peptide bond — formed between two amino acids via dehydration synthesis. The chain of amino acids linked by peptide bonds is called a polypeptide.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d7">
        <div class="q-num">Question 7</div>
        <div class="q-text">Which mutation causes <span class="key">more overall change</span> — substitution or addition? Why?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d7',false)">Substitution — it changes the most important base</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d7',true)">Addition — it causes a frameshift, changing every amino acid after the mutation site</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d7',false)">They cause equal amounts of change</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d7',false)">Substitution — it affects the entire reading frame</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d7-fb">Addition — inserting a base shifts the entire reading frame, scrambling every codon after the mutation point. Substitution usually only changes one codon and therefore one amino acid.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d8">
        <div class="q-num">Question 8</div>
        <div class="q-text">Can a mutation be <span class="key">neutral</span> — causing no change to the protein?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d8',false)">No — every mutation changes the protein</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d8',true)">Yes — multiple codons can code for the same amino acid</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d8',false)">Only if the mutation occurs in tRNA</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d8',false)">Only frameshift mutations can be neutral</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d8-fb">Yes — this is called a silent or neutral mutation. The genetic code is redundant: multiple codons code for the same amino acid. So a base change may produce a different codon that still codes for the same amino acid, leaving the protein unchanged.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d9">
        <div class="q-num">True or False</div>
        <div class="q-text">In DNA, adenine always pairs with <span class="key">guanine</span>.</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d9',false)">True</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d9',true)">False</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d9-fb">False — adenine (A) pairs with thymine (T), and cytosine (C) pairs with guanine (G). Remember: A-T and C-G are the complementary base pairs in DNA.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d10">
        <div class="q-num">True or False</div>
        <div class="q-text">Transcription converts DNA into <span class="key">mRNA</span>.</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d10',true)">True</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d10',false)">False</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d10-fb">True — transcription happens in the nucleus where DNA is used as a template to produce mRNA. The mRNA then travels to the ribosome for translation into protein.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-d11">
        <div class="q-num">Fill in the blank</div>
        <div class="q-text">The three steps of translation are: initiation, ________, and ________.</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d11',false)">replication → termination</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d11',false)">transcription → elongation</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d11',true)">elongation → termination</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'d11',false)">elongation → replication</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="d11-fb">Initiation → Elongation → Termination. Initiation = ribosome assembles at start codon. Elongation = amino acid chain builds. Termination = stop codon reached, protein released.</div>
      </div>

