    <!-- NEUROSIM -->
    <div class="sub-panel2" id="sub2-neurosim">
      <div class="section-label" style="margin-top:0">NeuroSim — Giant Squid Action Potential</div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns1">
        <div class="q-num">Question 1</div>
        <div class="q-text">What does <span class="key">TTX (Tetrodotoxin)</span> do to the action potential?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns1',false)">Blocks K+ channels — AP fires but won't come back down</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns1',true)">Blocks Na+ channels — no AP can be produced</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns1',false)">Prevents Na+ channel inactivation — AP never returns to resting</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns1',false)">Increases the threshold stimulus needed</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns1-fb">TTX blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels. Since Na+ rushing in is what causes depolarization, no Na+ in = no action potential. The membrane stays at resting potential.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns2">
        <div class="q-num">Question 2</div>
        <div class="q-text">What does <span class="key">TEA (Tetraethylammonium)</span> do to the action potential?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns2',false)">Blocks Na+ channels — no AP fires</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns2',true)">Blocks K+ channels — AP fires but cannot repolarize</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns2',false)">Blocks both Na+ and K+ channels</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns2',false)">Eliminates the threshold stimulus</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns2-fb">TEA blocks K+ channels. K+ flowing OUT is what brings the membrane back down during repolarization. Without it, the AP fires but stays elevated — it can't come back down to resting potential.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns3">
        <div class="q-num">Question 3</div>
        <div class="q-text">What does <span class="key">Scorpion Toxin</span> do to the action potential?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns3',false)">Blocks Na+ channels only</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns3',false)">Blocks K+ channels only</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns3',true)">Prevents Na+ channel inactivation and blocks K+ — AP never comes down</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns3',false)">Increases Na+ permeability permanently</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns3-fb">Scorpion toxin keeps Na+ channels from inactivating AND blocks K+ channels — so Na+ keeps rushing in and K+ can't flow out. The AP fires and never returns to resting. No regulation of either pump.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns4">
        <div class="q-num">Question 4</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is the <span class="key">absolute refractory period</span>?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns4',false)">A period where a stronger stimulus can still trigger a second AP</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns4',true)">A period where NO stimulus, regardless of strength, can trigger another AP</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns4',false)">The delay between stimulus and start of the AP</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns4',false)">The time it takes Na+ to reset after an AP</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns4-fb">Absolute refractory period — Na+ channels are inactivated (not just closed). No amount of stimulation can open them again until they fully reset. This is why APs don't overlap and travel in one direction.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns5">
        <div class="q-num">Question 5</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is the <span class="key">relative refractory period</span>?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns5',false)">No stimulus can trigger a second AP</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns5',true)">A stronger than normal stimulus CAN trigger a second AP</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns5',false)">The membrane is at its peak depolarization</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns5',false)">Na+ channels are fully inactivated</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns5-fb">Relative refractory period — some Na+ channels have reset, but K+ channels are still open causing hyperpolarization. A second AP IS possible but requires a stronger stimulus than normal to overcome the hyperpolarized state.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns6">
        <div class="q-num">Question 6</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is the <span class="key">latent period</span>?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns6',false)">The peak of the action potential</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns6',false)">The period after the AP where the cell can't fire again</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns6',true)">The delay between the stimulus and the start of the AP response</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns6',false)">The time it takes K+ channels to open</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns6-fb">The latent period is the brief delay between when a stimulus is applied and when the action potential actually begins. During this time the membrane is building toward threshold.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns7">
        <div class="q-num">True or False</div>
        <div class="q-text">During the <span class="key">absolute refractory period</span>, a stronger stimulus can still trigger a second AP.</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns7',false)">True</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns7',true)">False</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns7-fb">False — absolute means absolute. Na+ channels are completely inactivated. No stimulus of any strength can produce another AP until they reset. That's what makes it different from the relative refractory period.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-ns8">
        <div class="q-num">True or False</div>
        <div class="q-text">TEA blocks <span class="key">sodium</span> channels.</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns8',false)">True</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'ns8',true)">False</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="ns8-fb">False — TEA blocks potassium (K+) channels. TTX is the one that blocks sodium (Na+) channels. Easy way to remember: TTX = Na+ blocked = no AP at all. TEA = K+ blocked = AP fires but can't come back down.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="section-label">Quick Match — Drugs &amp; Effects</div>
      <div class="match-score-bar">
        <div class="match-score-txt">Matched: <strong id="mmns-score">0</strong> / 4</div>
        <button class="reset-btn" onclick="buildMatchG('mmns')">Shuffle &amp; Retry</button>
      </div>
      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:8px;margin-bottom:8px;">
        <div class="match-col-lbl">Drug / term</div><div class="match-col-lbl">What it does</div>
      </div>
      <div class="match-cols" id="mmns-left-wrap" style="display:contents;"></div>
      <div class="match-complete" id="mmns-complete">All matched! You know your neurotoxins.</div>
    </div>

    <!-- BLOOD PRESSURE -->
    <div class="sub-panel2" id="sub2-bp">
      <div class="section-label" style="margin-top:0">Blood Pressure — Questions</div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp1">
        <div class="q-num">Question 1</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is the <span class="key">normal blood pressure</span> reading?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp1',false)">80/120 mmHg</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp1',true)">120/80 mmHg</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp1',false)">140/90 mmHg</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp1',false)">100/60 mmHg</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp1-fb">120/80 mmHg — 120 is systolic (during contraction), 80 is diastolic (at rest). Don't mix up the order on the exam.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp2">
        <div class="q-num">Question 2</div>
        <div class="q-text">What does the <span class="key">systolic</span> number represent?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp2',false)">Pressure in the arteries when the heart is at rest</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp2',true)">Pressure in the arteries when the heart contracts</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp2',false)">The average of systolic and diastolic</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp2',false)">The pressure in the veins</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp2-fb">Systolic = contraction. When the heart beats and pushes blood out, pressure in the arteries peaks — that's the top number. Memory trick: Systolic = Squeeze.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp3">
        <div class="q-num">Question 3</div>
        <div class="q-text">What does the <span class="key">diastolic</span> number represent?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp3',false)">Pressure during heart contraction</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp3',true)">Pressure in the arteries when the heart is at rest between beats</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp3',false)">The total blood volume</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp3',false)">The pulse rate per minute</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp3-fb">Diastolic = relaxation. Between heartbeats, the heart fills back up. The pressure in the arteries drops to its lowest point — that's the bottom number. Memory trick: Diastolic = Down/resting.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp4">
        <div class="q-num">Question 4</div>
        <div class="q-text">What is <span class="key">hypertension</span>?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp4',false)">Abnormally low blood pressure</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp4',true)">Chronically elevated blood pressure, typically above 140/90 mmHg</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp4',false)">A temporary spike in BP during exercise</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp4',false)">Normal BP in elderly patients</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp4-fb">Hypertension = high blood pressure, chronically above 140/90 mmHg. It often has no symptoms (called the "silent killer") but causes serious long-term damage to the heart, vessels, kidneys, and brain.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp5">
        <div class="q-num">Question 5</div>
        <div class="q-text">Which of the following is a <span class="key">negative effect</span> of long-term high blood pressure?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp5',false)">Increased bone density</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp5',true)">Stroke, heart attack, kidney damage, and vision loss</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp5',false)">Lower resting heart rate</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp5',false)">Improved circulation</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp5-fb">Chronically high BP damages arterial walls, forces the heart to work harder, and strains organs that depend on healthy blood flow — especially the kidneys, brain, eyes, and heart itself.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp6">
        <div class="q-num">Question 6</div>
        <div class="q-text">What might <span class="key">extremely low blood pressure</span> indicate?</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp6',false)">The patient is very physically fit</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp6',false)">Normal aging process</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp6',true)">Dehydration, significant blood loss, heart failure, or shock</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp6',false)">Hypertension in disguise</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp6-fb">Extremely low BP (hypotension) means not enough blood is reaching organs. Causes include dehydration, hemorrhage (blood loss), heart failure, or septic/anaphylactic shock. It can be life-threatening if severe.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="q-card" id="card-bp7">
        <div class="q-num">True or False</div>
        <div class="q-text">The <span class="key">systolic</span> pressure is always lower than the diastolic pressure.</div>
        <div class="btn-row">
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp7',false)">True</button>
          <button class="opt-btn" onclick="choose(this,'bp7',true)">False</button>
        </div>
        <div class="feedback" id="bp7-fb">False — systolic is always HIGHER. It's the pressure during contraction (peak force). Diastolic is the lower number, representing pressure at rest. 120 systolic / 80 diastolic — the bigger number is always on top.</div>
      </div>

