  <!-- TOOLS & METHODS -->
  <div class="top-panel" id="panel-tools">
    <div class="section-label" style="margin-top:0">Tools &amp; Methods — Quick Reference</div>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:#888;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Know what equipment was used and how each lab was conducted.</p>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-disease">Macromolecules Lab</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <span>Tools:</span> Test tubes, hot water bath / hot plate, brown paper towel, dropper, wax pencil, iodine, Benedict's reagent, Biuret reagent, salad oil (positive control for lipids), glucose solution, starch solution, egg albumin.<br><br>
        <span>Method:</span> First ran positive and negative controls for each test to know what results look like. Then tested 3 food samples with all 4 tests (Benedict's, iodine, Biuret, paper test). Recorded color changes and translucency. Wrote formal lab report with hypothesis, data tables, and conclusion.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-disease">Osmolarity &amp; Tonicity Lab</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <span>Tools:</span> Microscope, slides, cover slips, lancet, alcohol swab, microhematocrit tubes (heparinized), NaCl solutions (1%, 2%, 3%, 5%), distilled water (dH₂O), onion membrane (optional).<br><br>
        <span>Method:</span> Finger prick to collect own blood. Made slides with blood + DI water (hypotonic) and blood + 5% NaCl (hypertonic) to observe extreme effects. Then mixed blood with varying NaCl concentrations (1–3%) until RBCs maintained normal shape — that concentration = isotonic. Measured and recorded RBC size and shape under microscope at each concentration.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-disease">Neuromuscular Reflexes Lab</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <span>Tools:</span> Reflex hammer, Neurosim (computer simulation software).<br><br>
        <span>Method:</span> Used reflex hammer to test patellar reflex and Babinski reflex on lab partner. Graded reflexes on a 0–4+ scale (2+ = normal). Used Neurosim to simulate nerve and muscle electrophysiology and observe how stimuli affect reflex responses.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-disease">Urinalysis Lab</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <span>Tools:</span> Refractometer, dipstick reagent strips, microscope, slides, centrifuge, first morning urine sample.<br><br>
        <span>Method:</span> Used refractometer to measure specific gravity. Dipped reagent strip into urine and compared color changes to chart (tested pH, glucose, protein, etc.). Centrifuged urine to get sediment, made slide, examined under microscope for cells, bacteria, and crystals.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-card">
      <div class="tip-disease">EMG Lab</div>
      <div class="tip-body">
        <span>Tools:</span> iWorx EMG system, surface skin electrodes (placed on forearm), hand grip dynamometer. EMG measured in mV, force in PSI.<br><br>
        <span>Method:</span> Part A — performed 5 grips of increasing strength, recorded both EMG signal and force output each time. Observed positive linear relationship between force and EMG. Part B — held maximum grip until force dropped to 50% of max, recording how long it took and how force declined over time (muscle fatigue).
      </div>
    </div>

